\c 19
\cl Ezechiel 19
\cd The parable of the young lions; and of the vine that is wasted.
\p
\v 1 Moreover *take thou up a lamentation for the princes of Israel,
\p
\v 2 And say: Why did thy mother, the lioness, lie down among the lions, and bring up her whelps in the midst of young lions?
\p
\v 3 And she brought out one of her whelps, and he became a lion: and he learned to catch the prey, and to devour men.
\p
\v 4 And the nations heard of him, and took him, but not without receiving wounds: and they brought him in chains into the land of Egypt.
\p
\v 5 But she seeing herself weakened, and that her hope was lost, took one of her young lions, and set him up for a lion.
\p
\v 6 And he went up and down among the lions, and became a lion: and he learned to catch the prey, and to devour men.
\p
\v 7 He learned to make widows, and to lay waste their cities: and the land became desolate, and the fulness thereof, by the noise of his roaring.
\p
\v 8 And the nations came together against him on every side out of the provinces, and they spread their net over him, in their wounds he was taken.
\p
\v 9 And they put him into a cage, they brought him in chains to the king of Babylon: and they cast him into prison, that his voice should no more be heard upon the mountains of Israel.
\p
\v 10 Thy mother is like a vine in thy blood, planted by the water: her fruit and her branches have grown out of many waters.
\p
\v 11 And she hath strong rods, to make sceptres for them that bear rule, and her stature was exalted among the branches: and she saw her height in the multitude of her branches.
\p
\v 12 But she was plucked up in wrath, and cast on the ground, *and the burning wind dried up her fruit: her strong rods are withered, and dried up: the fire hath devoured her.
\p
\v 13 And now she is transplanted into the desert, in a land not passable, and dry.
\p
\v 14 And a fire is gone out from a rod of her branches, which hath devoured her fruit: so that she now hath no strong rod, to be a sceptre of rulers. This is a lamentation, and it shall be for a lamentation.
\f + \fr 19:1\ft Year of the World 3411.\f*
\x + \xo 19:12\xt Osee 13:15.\x*
\f + \fr 19:1\ft Princes: sons of Josias, who were so wretched. The latter part of this beautiful canticle, or allegory, (ver. 10.) regards Sedecias. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 19:2\ft Lioness; Jerusalem (Challoner) which made alliances with the lions, or nations. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 19:3\ft Whelps; Joachaz, or Sellum, (Challoner) who reigned only three months, like his brother Jechonias. (Haydock) --- The four last kings were all cruel. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 19:4\ft But. Hebrew, "he was taken in their pit," (Protestants; Haydock) as also [in] ver. 8. Septuagint, "in his or their corruption." We do not read that Joachaz fought, (Calmet) though this passage insinuates as much. (Sanctius) (4 Kings 23:30., etc.)\f*
\f + \fr 19:5\ft Lions: Joakim. (Challoner) --- He reigned eleven years; but was such a monster, that the prophet does not speak of him or bewail his fate, 4 Kings 23:34., and Jeremias 22:19. His words are applicable to Jechonias alone; who was cruel, and banished to Babylon, ver. 8. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 19:8\ft Nations: rovers of Chaldea, Syria, etc., 4 Kings 24:2. (Worthington) --- Wounds. Hebrew, "pit." He was besieged, (4 Kings 24:11.; Calmet) and gave himself up. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 19:10\ft Blood. She has given birth to many kings. (Menochius) --- The original may be inaccurate, and perhaps should be, "a vine-tree or branch:" (Calmet) cormoc instead of bedammecha. Septuagint read kerimmon, "like a rose-flower," planted, etc. (Haydock) --- He speaks of Sedecias more obscurely. (Calmet) --- The kingdom had flourished under David and Solomon. It afterwards lost its splendour under wicked kings, and all the tribes were removed. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 19:11\ft Rods. The king had many children, and confided in them, but they were slain.\f*
\f + \fr 19:13\ft Dry; unfit for vine-trees. He speaks of the prison of Babylon. (Calmet) --- The country was naturally wet. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 19:14\ft Fire. Ismael, who slew Godolias, was of the royal family, Jeremias xli., etc. (Calmet)\f*
